        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2652522275?book_show_action=true">Jan 07, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rockossack" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rockossack" href="/user/show/26458463-rockossack">Rockossack</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/6619722-warriors-of-god">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26458463-rockossack?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2652522275" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17973043806572616523">It is more of a &quot;meh&quot; than an &quot;OK&quot; book. The author is obsessed with the alleged intimate relationship between Richard and Philip II, going as far as almost solely portraying 5 years’ worth of conflict between England and France as something that ex-lovers are expected to do. But this is just the epilogue of the book, according to the Crusading chapters most of the English-French antagonism during the Crusade itself could be derived from Richard and Philip being bad exes. I also felt that the po</span>
  <span id="freeText17973043806572616523" style="display:none">It is more of a "meh" than an "OK" book. The author is obsessed with the alleged intimate relationship between Richard and Philip II, going as far as almost solely portraying 5 years’ worth of conflict between England and France as something that ex-lovers are expected to do. But this is just the epilogue of the book, according to the Crusading chapters most of the English-French antagonism during the Crusade itself could be derived from Richard and Philip being bad exes. I also felt that the portrayal of Saladin was biased. Now that I think about it, I am hard pressed to find any criticism of Saladin that I read here.<br /><br />Still, it is a bit more than 1 stars for me as it was an easy enough read that occasionally entertained me with fun anecdotes - albeit, I am not sure about the authenticity of the sources behind them. ("She must have been a stolid Viking wench, for Philip Augustus fled the bridal chamber in terror on their wedding night, never to return. He immediately divorced the saucy Dane." - yeah, history finds this debatable).<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17973043806572616523" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


